Day#05 - Motion Sickness and latency

Introduction - Many VR users experience extreme nausea or dizziness while using a VR headset. That's because of motion sickness or latency in 
system.

Motion Sickness - 
--Motion sickness is caused due to sensory mismatch.
--This can happen when the player is the VR World is moving and the physical body is still.
--This mismatch between eyes and brain can cause motion sickness.

Latency in VR - 
--As learnt in our previous days, high latency is VR can cause nausea and discomfort.
--This is because there is a difference in time between the users head movement and its update in the virtual world.
--High latency can make the virtual world feel unresponsive and may cause motion sickness.

Motion-to-photon latency - 
--This is the total time between the users head movement and the movement reflected on the display.
--This depends on several factors like sensors,tracking system,etc.
--Modern VR Headsets try to keep this delay as low as possible to improve comfort.

Real World Example - 
--Meta Quest 3 uses low latency tracking, fast display and high refresh rates to reduce motion sickness and give the user a better experience.

Conclusion - 
Today I learnt that motion sickness is caused due to the mismatch of what our eyes see on display and what our body feels. I also learnt Motion-to-photon
latency which should be as less as possible for a comforting VR experience. For a smooth and enjoyable VR experience latency must be as low as possible.

